article.headline: Bell scores 18 vs. former team
article.linkText: Jazz rally to snap Mavs' 9-game win streak
article.story: SALT LAKE CITY (AP) -- Andrei Kirilenko's ankle is feeling better, although his nerves were a little frayed. Kirilenko had 23 points and 10 rebounds in his second game from a sprained ankle and the Utah Jazz held on for a 91-88 win over Dallas, ending the Mavericks' nine-game winning streak. Dallas had two 3-pointers that would have forced overtime bounce off the rim in the final seconds. "Yeah, I was scared. My heart went thump-thump-thump-thump," said Kirilenko, who also had five assists and two blocks in Utah's second win in three games against Dallas this season. Raja Bell finished with 18 points against his former team, making two key free throws with 12.3 seconds left. But Utah, which rallied from an eight-point deficit in the fourth quarter, couldn't celebrate until the Mavericks had missed their final two shots. Michael Finley, who scored 29, put up a tying attempt in the closing seconds that bounced off the rim. The Mavs were outrebounded 45-24, but managed to get one when they needed it most and kicked it out to Antoine Walker. But his shot, too, bounced off the rim and just missed rolling in before the buzzer sounded. "It is really like double slow motion," Bell said. "The ball's up, it bounces once, it bounces twice, gets kicked out and you're kind of holding your breath." Dallas hadn't lost since Jan. 11, when Detroit beat the Mavericks 115-102. After allowing nearly twice as many rebounds in the second of back-to-back games, there wasn't a great chance to continue the winning streak. "Basically when you get outrebounded as bad as we did tonight, it's awful hard to win," Mavericks coach Don Nelson said. The Jazz had lost five straight until a 98-93 win over the Clippers on Monday. That was also Kirilenko's first game back after missing four straight and Utah's improvement has been apparent. But Jazz coach Jerry Sloan was equally pleased with Bell, who signed with Utah as a free agent after spending last season in Dallas. "If you see a guy playing as hard as he was, it's got to rub off on the other guys out there," Sloan said. "He's got some toughness. He's not afraid. He will stand up and fight. That's been lacking in our team." The Mavericks were playing one night after a 118-116 win at Seattle, but didn't seem the least bit tired in their second straight thriller. "It hurt us in the first half, but we found some energy and got back into the game," Nelson said. After trailing throughout the third quarter, Finley and Antawn Jamison combined for four consecutive 3-pointers to turn a 66-64 deficit into a 76-70 lead early in the fourth quarter. Finley added a layup on a nice pass in the lane by Steve Nash, but the Jazz starting hitting their shots again. Kirilenko made a 3-pointer, Bell drove for a layup and Kirilenko hit another 3 that got the Utah fans roaring and on their feet. Utah forced a turnover and DeShawn Stevenson tied it at 80-all with two free throws, then Ostertag drew a foul and gave the Jazz a brief lead by going 1-for-2 from the line with 3:40 left. The teams remained within three points of each other the rest of the way. Shawn Bradley drove for a one-handed dunk that got the Mavericks to 89-88 in the final minute, but that was it for the Mavericks. Bell, who played for Dallas last season and had a career-high 25 points in 99-90 victory over the Mavs on Jan. 5, was perfect from the line to force Dallas into going for a 3-pointer at the end.< ^Notes: Michael Ruffin and Greg Ostertag each pulled down 11 rebounds for Utah. ... Nowitzki and Jazz G Raul Lopez got tangled early in the fourth quarter and the 7-foot Nowitzki took a wild swing as he broke loose. He missed the 6-foot, 160-pound point guard and was booed loudly. ... The Mavericks placed guard Tony Delk on the injured list with a sprained left ankle and activated forward Eduardo Najera. ... The Jazz signed center Mikki Moore ... Utah rookie point guard Mo Williams did not dress because of a sprained left ankle.
